other_tests.procedure_name: Total Hip Arthroplasty with Cement (Left Side)
other_tests.findings: The procedure was noted to be particularly difficult. The osseous surfaces were devoid of any cancellous bone. The cortex was sclerotic and brittle. The acetabulum was small with a deficient anterior wall.

other_tests.procedure_name: Total Hip Replacement with Cement (Right Side)
other_tests.findings: The procedure was technically challenging, resulting in shattering of the cortex on the lateral aspect of the femur distal to the greater trochanter.
Chronic osteomyelitis of the right tibia developed, requiring treatment.
Pathological fractures developed in both tibiae, treated nonoperatively in plaster casts.
A stress fracture of the right femur developed distal to the tip of the prosthesis.

other_tests.procedure_name: Nonoperative Management for Second Stress Fracture
other_tests.findings: A second stress fracture developed proximal to the tip of the prosthesis on the right side.
other_tests.changes_over_time: Resulted in a further varus deformity.

other_tests.findings: A stress fracture of the left femur developed at the tip of the prosthesis.
